1) Purpose

This document shall serve as a supplement to the team’s final report. It will simply provide supporting evidence to the figures and model results presented in our other material. The document is a consolidation of each member’s individual efforts into one file, and has been subset according to each respective model and process. Because the file has a lengthy output, the table of contents above can be used to quickly navigate the file to find supporting code for each section of the report and/or presentation. There may be sections of the document that have been commented out in order to not print out excessively large outputs or to mitigate run time spent on unnecessary, informational code.

4a) Create Corpus

## create corpus; convert the narrative field within the incidents dataset to the corpus; conduct the following preprocessing steps
## 1. convert all text to lower case, 2. remove punctuation, and 3. remove stopwords
incident_corpus <- Corpus(VectorSource(incidents2$narrative)) 
incident_corpus <- tm_map(incident_corpus, PlainTextDocument) 
incident_corpus <- tm_map(incident_corpus, tolower) 
incident_corpus <- tm_map(incident_corpus, removePunctuation)
incident_corpus <- tm_map(incident_corpus, removeWords, stopwords("english"))

8) Model Tuning

8a) Random Forest

# Set the control for train function (10-fold cross-validation)
rfcontrol <- trainControl(method="cv", number=10)

# Set up a grid of tuning parameters to explore
# In this case, let's consider mtry values from 2 to the max number of predictors
max_mtry <- ncol(iw3) - 1  # excluding the target variable
grid <- expand.grid(.mtry = seq(2, max_mtry, by = 10)) 


# Set seed for reproducibility
set.seed(1)

# Run Random Forest model
fit.rf <- train(type ~ ., 
                data = iw3, 
                method = "rf", 
                metric = "Accuracy", 
                tuneGrid = grid,
                trControl = rfcontrol)

# Print model results
print(fit.rf)
